    "created_at": "2018-06-11T23:02:13Z",
    "updated_at": "2018-06-11T23:04:43Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Oh, so it still hasn't been fixed, has it?  Sigh.  When I read both the relevant threads, back in October, it seemed clear that the Google guys felt that \"our way or the highway\" was appropriate.  And given that the *purpose* of GRPC is so you can access Google's servers, and NOT so you can write your own servers, that makes perfect sense.\r\n\r\nIf you actually want a decent RPC stack, can I suggest Thrift?  B/c really, GRPC's shit is weak.\r\n\r\nETA: in case it's not clear, I also asked for this to be fixed -- to enable passing the relevant callback down thru the GRPC layer to Node.JS' TLS layer.  As I understand it, there's a patch somebody wrote, that makes this possible.  But since I was only using GRPC with a client, and I've stopped working with that client, I no longer care. After all, Thrift doesn't have this problem (nor other problems that GRPC suffers from, e.g. lack of deterministic marshalling)."
